          "explanation": "We denote each inhabitant as either Knight (truth\u2011teller) or Knave (liar).  \n- Alice\u2019s statement \u201cBob is a knave\u201d must be true if Alice is a Knight, false if Alice is a Knave.  \n- Bob\u2019s statement \u201cAlice and Charlie are of the same type\u201d must be true if Bob is a Knight, false if Bob is a Knave.  \n- Charlie\u2019s statement \u201cAlice is a knave\u201d must be true if Charlie is a Knight, false if Charlie is a Knave.  \n\nTesting the eight possible assignments:\n\n1. (A=K, B=K, C=K) \u2013 Alice would require Bob to be a knave \u2192 contradiction.  \n2. (A=K, B=K, C=N) \u2013 same contradiction as 1.  \n3. (A=K, B=N, C=K) \u2013 Bob\u2019s false statement would require Alice and Charlie to differ, but they are both knights \u2192 contradiction.  \n4. (A=K, B=N, C=N) \u2013  \n   * Alice (K) says Bob is a knave \u2192 true (Bob is N).  \n   * Bob (N) says \u201cAlice and Charlie are the same\u201d \u2192 false, and indeed Alice (K) and Charlie (N) differ.  \n   * Charlie (N) says \u201cAlice is a knave\u201d \u2192 false, and Alice is a knight.  \n   All statements match the speakers\u2019 types, so this assignment is consistent.  \n5\u20118. All remaining assignments lead to at least one mismatch between a statement\u2019s truth value and the speaker\u2019s type.\n\nThus the only viable configuration is: Alice\u202f=\u202fknight, Bob\u202f=\u202fknave, Charlie\u202f=\u202fknave."
